result.execSummary:
The defendant Fayth Dayonna Rose Cook was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Fayth Dayonna Rose Cook in court.  Attorney Corey R. Flynn in court for Fayth Dayonna Rose Cook.  Prosecuting attorney Navjot Singh Hira in court for the State of Wisconsin. 

AS TO COUNT ONE; Defendant changes plea(s) to GUILTY. Defendant examined as to plea, advised of Constitutional Rights and the maximum penalties. Defendant further advised that if not a US citizen, deportation is possible. Court found that the defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived rights.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights form, Addendum, and Elements/Jury Instructions received and filed. Parties stipulate to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea(s).  Court found defendant GUILTY and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.    

as to count one; Defendant ordered to serve 30 DAYS in the House of Correction, credit of 0 days time served, Huber Privileges for WORK. Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on probation for 6 months with the following conditions:

- Sign up for probation no later than October 27th, 2022.
- No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause.
- Obtain/maintain full time work.
- Complete 50 hours of community service.
- Complete a cognitive thinking course.
- Submit a DNA sample by October 27th, 2022 and pay the surcharge by April 25th, 2023.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment/tax intercept

- Pay all MANDATORY costs, fees and surcharges by April 25th, 2023. Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment/tax intercept.
- Defendant advised of his right to appeal.

- Court GRANTS expungement with the successful completion on probation.
